{
  "$type": "Models.Core.Simulations, Models",
  "Version": 216,
  "Name": "Simulations",
  "ResourceName": null,
  "Children": [
    {
      "$type": "Models.Documentation, Models",
      "Text": "# Using a table to define an Experiment\n\nThis example will walk through the creation of experiments using an excel or csv file to define the permutations of an experiment. This example is useful for experiments where each permutation is fairly unique from each other, such as running the same simulation across multiple defined sites, or when you have only a subset of scenerios that would otherwise require running 100s of simulations to capture all the variations using a Permutation model.\n\n## FactorFromFile\n\n{[FactorFromFile]}\n\n## LimitedPermutation\n\nThe LimitedPermutation example shows how to use FactorFromFile to build an experiment where there are multiple treatments of different types and numbers. In this case, we have 7 barley trials, with various cultivar and fertilisation rules, along with 2 canola trials and a Chickpea that should all run in the same year on the same paddock for comparision. While this could be done with a normal permutation, it would produce additional simulations that we don't need, and require complex manager scripts to handle all the options.\n\nWith FactorFromFile, we cna instead just define the changes we want for each of our simulations, and use basic manager scripts from the Management Toolbox to build our simulation. In the csv file we have nine modifications to the simulation, This includes setting the crop on the sowing, fertilisation and harvesting scripts, setting the cultivar to plant, the sowing date and properties and fertiliser amounts and topups.\n\n| Column                                    | Value Type | Description                    |\n|-------------------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------|\n| Scenario                                  | Text       | Name of the simulation         |\n| Crop                                      | Text       | Extra simulation descriptor    |\n| [Sow on a fixed date].Script.Crop         | Model      | Crop model to sow              |\n| [Fertilise at sowing].Script.Crop         | Model      | Crop model to fertilise        |\n| [Harvesting].Script.Crop                  | Model      | Crop model to harvest          |\n| [Sow on a fixed date].Script.CultivarName | Text       | Cultivar to sow                |\n| [Sow on a fixed date].Script.SowDate      | Date       | Date to sow                    |\n| [Sow on a fixed date].Script.SowingDepth  | Number     | Depth of sowing                |\n| [Sow on a fixed date].Script.Population   | Number     | Population of sowing           |\n| [Fertilise at sowing].Script.Amount       | Number     | Amount of fertiliser at sowing |\n| [Topup fertiliser].Script.Amount          | Number     | Amount of fertiliser at top up |\n\nIn the case of the fertiliser changes, only three of the seven simulations have a value in those columns. When this is the case, that modification is ignored on any simulation that doesn't have a value, and whatever was defined in the simulation is used. If you instead want the value of something to be cleared (or made 'null'), then a value of *null* should be put into the table.\n\nThe table also contains the **Scenario** column that defines what the composite factors should be called, and a **Crop** column to help with filtering. You can see in the interface the factors that have been created, and that they are set to read only to signify they were generated. It would be entirely possible to create these composite factors by manually, however imagine that this experiment had 50 or 100 variations to run, then it would take a long time.\n\nDown in the GrainWt graph we take advantage of the crop column to set the different crops as different colours. We also use a trick in our report to allow graphing of all the crops together like this. By writing *\"([Barley].Grain.Wt + [Canola].Grain.Wt + [Chickpea].Grain.Wt) as Grain.Wt\"* we can get the grain weight of any of our crop types, rather then needing to report each one and graph seperately.\n\n## MultipleSites\n\nThe MultipleSites example demostrates how this can be used to build a simulation where the same management rules are applied across different locations. In this example we have 3 sites, Dably, Kingaroy and Lincoln, which each have their own soil, weather and sowing dates, along with irrigation at Kingaroy. \n\n",
      "Name": "Documentation",
      "ResourceName": null,
      "Children": [],
      "Enabled": true,
      "ReadOnly": false
    },
